"Netflix-like recommendations rely on the K-Nearest Neighbors (KNN) algorithm, which operates on the simple logic that birds of a feather flock together."
" In this system, every subscriber is treated as a unique data point in a massive digital space. "
"The coordinates of your data point are determined by your viewing history, ratings, and even the genres you hover over. "
"When Netflix wants to suggest a new series, the KNN algorithm searches for the $K$ number of users whose viewing habits are closest to yours—your nearest neighbors."
"To determine who these neighbors are, the system calculates the mathematical distance between your profile and others. "
"For example, if you and a user named Alice both have a high preference for Sci-Fi (9/10) and a low preference for Romance (2/10), the distance between your profiles is very small. Using the Euclidean Distance formula, $d = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}$, your distance from Alice would be approximately 1.41. Meanwhile, a user who loves Romance but hates Sci-Fi would be much further away (a distance of 9.90). "
"Because Alice is your closest neighbor, the algorithm assumes you’ll like what she’s binging.However, while KNN is incredibly intuitive, it is also a lazy learner."
" This means it doesn't build a permanent model; instead, it recalculates distances every time a recommendation is needed. For a giant like Netflix with millions of users, this becomes computationally expensive. "
"To keep your Top Picks loading instantly, they often supplement KNN with more complex machine learning techniques that can handle massive datasets more efficiently."